segments.text: were astronomical, the projections that are embodied in the project agreement.
In 1989, for example, the Woodlands would have built over 4,000 dwelling units.
We will do, in 1990, about 950 dwelling units, less than a quarter of what was projected to have been done last year.
In our best year, we did about 1,200 dwelling units, and that was in the heyday of Houston.
The project agreement contemplated we would have sold that many units, sold or built for rent that many units the first year in development.
So it's clearly over-optimistic if you want to give people the benefit of the doubt.
And then, too, we've added more land to the woodlands.
We've added 50 percent to the land mass of the woodlands.
So even if we had hit those projections, we'd still be about a third below completion, or where we should be in 1992.
So in 1992, if the date hadn't been in there, transition will occur because the Covenant's saying that it will.
And the Board will become resident-controlled.

The Woodlands Corporation will lose control of a very important institution in the Woodlands, very important to the servicing of the Woodlands and the marketing of the Woodlands, long before the Woodlands is 85% complete.
So we then had to say, well, what could we do?
We could not afford to lose control of the Woodlands.

or we could lose control of the WCA, but within the covenants, there's an entity that's created called the Development Standards Committee, and that is responsible for establishing design criteria, development standards, and approving all new construction that goes on in the Woodlands.
And the covenants say that the Woodlands Corporation would have control of the DSC,
through 1992 to August of 1992.
And then after that, it becomes a function of the WCA, which in 1992 becomes resident control.
That's like creating a planning commission or a zoning board controlled by the residents.
And then they could, if we were to continue the Woodlands Covenants on new properties, we would have to go to them and say, can we build this product again?
You know, and that's just not workable.

So while we wished the 1992 date were not in the covenants and that we could continue as we are now because it's working very well, and many residents have said to us, I wish we could continue because we like the involvement of the Women's Corporation.
We think it adds stability.
We think it adds quality.
We're going to honor the provisions of the covenants and
transfer of control of the board in 1992.
That leaves a large area of the Woodlands under the WCA.
We will create two new associations for the new areas of development, the residential association and the commercial association, which we will control until 85% of development.
And we're not going to put a date certain in those covenants.
We're not going to make the same mistake.
And so what we have is we honor transition.
We set up new associations.
And then we and the elected directors who now serve on the WCA board have put our heads together and say, is it best to have three associations operating independently?
Or is it better in some way to create a working relationship
where we can achieve economies of scale and efficiencies of management.
And by doing that, we all can benefit.
The obvious answer is yes, that would be best.
How could we do it?
And we have come up with the notion of a services corporation to which the WCA staff would be transferred.
And it would be...
corporation, a nonprofit corporation that administers the affairs of all three associations, responding to the wishes of the respective boards of each association.
So it's not an umbrella association.
It's a services corporation that works under contract with each of the associations and takes its marching orders from the boards of each of the associations.
That is what we have been presenting to the community.
It is a hard concept for people to understand because they have always thought that the woodlands would be served by one association.
Frankly, I think all of us have gotten so used to the one association that it's even hard for us to even contemplate setting up other associations.
And if there is any
or hesitancy on the part of the community.
It's, why are you changing things?
It's working so well.
Well, we're changing it because we, as a developer, have to know that we can be responsive to market conditions.
It's almost like what I described with HUD.
That was a very difficult partnership, and if we allowed the DSC

which would be resident-controlled, to be the throttle for new development, then we're not really having the freedom to make adjustments to the master plan as they need to be to change the product when the market says, you know, years ago we could build townhouses in the woodlands and sell them.
You couldn't sell a townhouse today.
So we've had to adjust our program.
We will get back into townhouse development, I'm sure, but for the time being, we'll have to wait.
And during the recession, you could not build apartments and rent them.
The vacancy rate in apartments was tremendous.
Well, the residents, some of the residents who are control-motivated don't fully appreciate that.
what a developer has to do to respond to market conditions and so forth.

And then you would have people coming and going on that development standards committee, whereas by creating the new associations, we set up the development standards committees within them, which we would control and have the continuity of the developer representation, have the professionalism of architects and engineers and developer type people on that committee.

We're setting up the other association, but trying to keep, through the Services Corporation, the notion which we all like, that is the unity of the woodlands, the cohesiveness of the woodlands, and... And the continuity of the... Continuity of services.
There'd still be one number to call if you need some help or have a question, and so forth.
The proposal is getting...
very good reception.
It's taking people a long time to understand why we have to do this.

And it's taking them time to understand that generally when they do, they call us or see them out on the streets and so forth, and they say, you know, we finally understand what you're trying to do, and it makes a lot of sense.
There are a handful of people, and literally I would say no more than a dozen people, who have
expressed vocal opposition to it.
And out of 30,000 people, you could expect some... What's the basis of their opposition?
They think the developer is trying to wrest control from the WCA.
They don't understand that the WCA board, which will be resident control, will be the authority for the WCA.
It's somehow in their minds.
They see the services corporation as being the controlling entity.
It is not.
It works at the behest of the board of the WCA or the board of WCA2, which is what we're calling it for lack of a name right now.
And they don't fully understand the relationship.
If you were to do an organizational chart, you would have the WCA board up here,
And then you would have the Services Corporation as a really dotted line relationship to the board, beneath the board.
It's not superior to the board.
And that's where they really don't understand that.
And what is your role in this transition?
Guiding it and making sure that it happens.
Your chief flag waver?
Well, I'm one of the authors.
of the transition proposal.
We had a committee of four who conceived it, then brought it to the board of the association, which endorsed it.
And now we're presenting it to the public, and presumably... Who were the other four?
Well, of the three, Scott Cummings, who's the general manager of the WCA, Eric Wojnar,
who works for the Women's Corporation, at that time was controller and serves as the treasurer of the WCA.
And Brian Reed, who was the attorney for the WCA.
Four of us conceived of this notion.
presented it to the board, and the people who really have to buy off on it are the four resident elected directors of the WCA.
The WCA has four of 11, seven of whom are appointed by the Women's Corporation, four of whom are elected by the community.
So what it came to was those four had to agree to it, and there were some substantial negotiations between the elected directors and the Women's Corporation.
Their biggest concern was if you stop the growth of the WCA, you freeze its tax base, much the way a city's tax base would be frozen if it could not annex.
And they wanted to annex the rest of the property.
And we explored that.
But it wouldn't work because it would undermine the economic viability of the second association.
So we said, well, how can we?
let you, the WCA, benefit from that growth but not annex those properties.
And what we came up with was a mechanism for sharing in certain costs of the WCA.
by the other associations who implicitly built in a bit of a subsidy.
So there is cash flowing from the other associations into the WCA to, in effect, subsidize.
It was a little bit complicated.
But that lowers the tax bite also.
But it would lower the tax bite of this.
From what you said, I gathered that the 1992 was a, I mean, there's no argument with that.
That was in the covenants.
It was a got-to-do.
That's right.
What other issues entered into your minds as you formulated this solution to that covenant?
What were the things that you kicked around before you came up with this idea?
Well, we had some objectives which we presented to the board four years ago.
We said...
This is why it's important to the Woodlands Corporation.
I'll see if I can remember that we said that.
We wanted whatever arrangement we came up with, we wanted the quality of services to be maintained.
We wanted the quality of facilities to be maintained.
We felt that an objective would be to lower the assessment rate
We said that we, the development corporation, needed to be in control of planning and development.
And there was one or two others.
And these sound very altruistic, but we've been altruistic for 16 years.
And we presented those to the elected directors.
And they said, gee, that sounds great.
We agree with that.
Now, how do we translate that into a plan of action?
That's what we worked for four years on.
And we came up with this.
And so those were the guiding principles, then?
Those were the guiding principles.
Have there been any basic tensions between the residents, say, and the population over the past years that are also involved, other than the expansion issue and the tax base, I guess, issue?
There have been issues from time to time that have produced tension.
In the early years,
The Woodlands Corporation people, not knowing anything about community management, made a mistake that so many developers still make.
And I lecture about this at the national conferences of community associations and to developers.
When you take fiduciary

responsibility of an association when you are the trustee of an association you have a responsibility to the residents like it or not that association is not your business it is a private nonprofit corporation that you for a time being have been entrusted to manage well
And most developers don't realize that, particularly if they're doing it for the first time.
In the early years, the Women's Corporation held the WCM meetings in somebody's office in this building.
And the residents are saying, that's our association.
We are members.
The Covenant's established us as members of the association.
We don't know what's going on.
Well, that got the Women's Corporation and the residents off on the wrong foot.
I mean, it really did in that last years.
suspicion developed that, well, a distrust between the company and the residents.
So they started holding public meetings.
But the manner in which those meetings were held only inflamed those suspicions.
The president and the board tended to like to call the majority he had on the board on all votes.
So it was clearly a rubber stamp situation, even when I first got on the board in 77.
And the residents just resented that, and I personally think for good reason.
Also, some of the tensions were heightened by the fact that
The residents only had one representative on board.
The board at that time, I think, was seven.
And it has grown.
It was eight.
Yeah, I think seven developer appointed and one resident elected.
So the development corporation, over time, began to see that it needed to change its style.
And in response to requests from the community, which were militant requests, added resident elected people to the board even before the covenants required them to be added.
And in some case, we gave up our seats.

to enable that to happen in fact today one of our seats is held by a resident elected director we should have eight seats we only have seven because we gave up one seat so those are some of the tensions in the early years and when i took over the presidency of the board which i've had for 10 years my objectives were to
eliminate those tensions and establish a partnership.

I changed the mode of operating the board and I have encouraged even our own appointed people with the responsibility of the trust that has been given to them for proper management of the association.
to speak out as the professionals that they are.
And if they don't agree with something, I want to hear that.
And we've made it a much stronger association as a result a couple of years ago.
We were named the best managed large scale association in the Houston area and hope to win that award this year at the national level.
They've just established a competition that I think will certainly come in the top two or three if not winning.
And that's because I like to use the talents I have available to me and foolish not to.
Other tensions tend to crop up.
between the community and the Women's Corporation on specific issues.
Most of them have to do with, well, I shouldn't say

I mean, there have been some issues where I think the community felt we were not protecting the standards of development as much as we should, such as one was when our first gas station was proposed for the Woodlands.
I think it's an Exxon station.
They were going to cut a driveway directly onto Grosvenor Road, which would have been taking trees down and having them cleaned up.
And the community virtually chained themselves in front of the bulldozers.
And they could go quite to that, but it was close to that.
And so we asked Exxon if they would change their plan, and they said okay.
Exxon didn't want to do it because it would cost them money, but they agreed because of the opposition.
And last I heard, that was the largest bro-sink gas station in the Houston area without a direct curb cutout to Grover's Mill.
They've objected to signs, certain types of signs that were proposed to be put in.
These are things that usually get resolved amicably.
But those are good kind of objections, too.
What you're saying is the residents care very deeply about the community.
That's right.
It's basically supportive of the whole framework.
Yeah, that's right.
We had a major controversy when we built and filled Lake Woodlands.
The community felt that they were not going to have enough access to the lake, and that became a big issue.
So we adjusted our plans to get more points of access to the lake.
Again, a feeling of this is our community, and we want to be part of it.
We don't want to.
And, you know, some of this is good.
Last year, or earlier this year, just outside of the developed areas, some of the people who owned the mineral rights kind of drilled a gas well.
We try to buy up all the mineral rights, mainly to prevent wells from being driven nearby or even in developed areas.
Had we controlled all the mineral rights, that well never would have been built.
But we didn't, so under state law you have to allow them.
To drill it, we put in conditions in the contract.
Thus, we controlled enough of the mineral rights and the surface rights to use quiet generators and things like that.
But the community was just upset that there would be an oil well or a gas well, as it turned out, being drilled within eye contact of existing homes.
And it had gotten noisy at times.
Yeah, we caught the flak very directly.
But that's something that we could not stop, although we tried to dissuade people from doing it.
So it tends to be single-issue, single-issue oriented, and those issues come and go, and we almost always...
and Women's Community Association takes over, will that sort of diminish some of your problems, maybe, or create new ones?
Do you see any different direction that that group may pursue in terms of what their goals are?
Well, I see a board that will have, when it starts out, ten elected and one appointed person.
We still have one residual person on the board.

Because it's predominantly elected and controlled by those people becoming very political, I think it will become political internal to the board, but I think it will also become much more political within the community and vis-a-vis the developing corporation.
I see seats being heavily contested.
I see a lot of what's going on.
in public politics now happening on the board.
And I think that board will make the United Times become militant vis-a-vis the Development Corporation.
So you see that as a divisive, or potentially divisive?
Could be, yeah.
Now, we have tried to be responsive.
We sit down with whatever community group has a problem.
I can't tell you the hours we put into that.
Not only myself, that's my job, but all the executives in this company.
If there's somebody in the community that wants an audience, give them the audience.
I just think that because the WCA board will have people actively vying for those seats, and some of them will be running negative campaigns,
They'll have campaign pledges that they'll have to keep.
And from time to time, we've had some very negative people on the board, and it was hard dealing with them.
People will use the WCA as a springboard to other political offices.
We had one fellow who wanted to run for Congress.
He wasn't known in the community, so he ran for the WCA board.
He found Rob Lapp had done something wrong in carrying out the elections and ran against Rob Lapp, saying he's trying to prevent fair elections.
This guy got the largest number of votes that were ever cast in a WCA election before or since.
He won hands down.
And then Rob left shortly thereafter.
I was the one who had to work with him.
And he said to me, he said, I'm using the WCA as my stepping stone to run for Congress.
I'll get name recognition.
And he said, I'm going to do some things you're not going to like.
But he said, I got to do them.
And sure enough, within a couple of years he was on the board, he kept us off balance all the time.
issue after issue.
He was in the newspapers all the time.
And, you know, we'd have lunch, and he'd say, you know, I hate to do this to you because I like you.
I said, I'm running for Congress.
So that's not going to end.
No, that's going to increase.
I think it's going to increase.
I think we're going to see that kind of dynamic happening.
So you've got a job there.
What about, speaking of tensions, I don't know if this is a good time.
Do you want to take a break or something?
That's fine.
Please do.
What about the tensions, say, with the county?
I know you said the Montgomery County problems and High Road problems and this kind of thing.
Can you comment on that?
Yeah.
And maybe even use the broader context.
Well, no.
Let me go at a national level.
All right.
As a student of Newtown's.

When you build a new town, with the exception of Roosevelt Island, which is probably the only one built inside the city, in order to amass the land, you've got to go far out where land is plentiful and cheap.
And so what you're doing is you're introducing an urban population into a rural area.
That's point number one.
There are lifestyle differences that the rural people don't really appreciate.
Number two, you're introducing a large population into a county that generally has a relatively small population.
That does several things.

It places demands on services and county government and the school and hospital district or whatever other public entities there are, notwithstanding the fact that you're bringing in a concomitant tax base, particularly if it's a mixed-use development.
The woman's more than pays its way in taxes and generates.
But you're taking institutions that haven't had to gear up
very much, and putting pressures on them.
You're also, by introducing a large population into an area, threatening the political structure.
And you're bringing voters in, voters who have no past allegiance to anybody who's held office.
We have, for example, a county clerk who's held office for 26 years.
who's now having to campaign.
He's never had to campaign before.
Okay, so there is a perceived threat to the established political order.
And, in fact, there's a real threat because these people are, you know, they have achieved their positions.
They have become known.
And if you take the kind of growth that the women's represents, you know, 30,000 people in 16 years, which is equal to, you know, Conroe 16 years ago had 7,500 people.
The new people aren't going to vote without any real knowledge of who's who and what their records have been, what their achievements have been, good, bad, or otherwise.
So it's a real threat.
Every new town that I'm aware of has met with hostility in the county and the nearest town that is approximate to the new town.
It's a phenomenon.
I mean, to this day, you can go to Columbia, Maryland, and pick up the newspaper, and you have the Columbians and the Howard County people still battling heads-on in the newspapers.
Politically, taking over the county, all of the elected offices, the majority of them are held by political people from Columbia.
That dynamic happened here.
And there are resentments between Conroe and the Woodlands, the rest of the county and the Woodlands.
And no matter what we do, we can't overcome it.
And frankly, given the history of the other new towns, I'm not sure that we ever will.
Until Conroe urbanizes enough itself with new people that they don't carry the old biases.
But that's, at best, a long time in time.
We've worked closely with them.
We've worked professionally with them.
And the senior manager of this company volunteers a lot of time on the boards
charities up there.
I can't tell you how many boards of directors I serve on them.
I can't tell you because I'm not sure I know.
I think it's six or eight.
And I spend hours.
And on a one-on-one, one-to-one, it's great.
Joel and Joe get along great.
But institutionally, there's always a distance.
What about the relationship with Houston and the city itself?
Does the Woodlands even fit into the purview of Houston?
Well, we are by choice, by our own initiative, in the extraterritorial jurisdiction of the city of Houston.
And that is because it is Mr. Mitchell's objective that at some point in time, Houston will annex the Woodlands.
that we will not be a freestanding, incorporated community.
Now that's one of the tensions.
That's an issue that pops up about every three or four years.
People look at it.
They don't do anything about it.
But I think as Houston starts to annex Northwood, that's going to become perhaps the major issue in the history of the Woodlands.
I think we're just buying time right now.
You know, the reason for wanting to be part of Houston has to do with what you're seeing as the older cities getting financially choked by the surrounding suburban cities.
And he feels as from an urban

uh growth standpoint but cities have to expand their their tax base that's in effect what we did with the wca good we've given the wca claims to some of the revenue streams on the new associations and frankly as a guy who has studied this a lot in school and since

somehow I think if there's a reconciliation that will take place between the suburban areas not wanting to be incorporated, I'm sorry, not wanting to be annexed by Houston, but Houston having a need to expand its economic base, it would be to find, work out some
economic relationship, sharing of the tax base that's represented in suburbia with the central city, but yet letting suburbia have political autonomy.
Has that happened here?
Oh yeah, all over the country.
It's called metropolitan government.
I can't name them all, but the ones I'm familiar with are Miami-Dade County,
That issue's going on with Webster, Clinton, and all the weird stuff.
Sure it is.
Minneapolis, St. Paul is one of the Metropolitan Government.
Phoenix has Metropolitan Government.
And these take various forms.
Some of them are strictly economic.
In some cases, Metropolitan Government actually elects a council and carries out certain things.
But from my standpoint, if you look at transportation,
If you look at subsidence, if you look at sewage treatment, if you look at water, those are foreign examples.
Those can all be and probably should be administered at a metropolitan scope.
through not individual cities or individual communities.
What about other services like police, fire?
Police and fire in schools are held very close to the hearts of local communities and ought to be administered locally.
The characteristics of the different communities probably can even justify different approaches to those things.
Those are the three things that I would say, above all, ought to be retained at the local level.
And those are things that require a lot of interaction between the community and whoever's delivering those services.
And those services, those delivery agents, have to be responsive to the local communities.
I think those ought to be local derivatives.
But frankly, I don't care who treats the waste that leaves my house, be it through the sewer system or garbage collection.
And that's a very simplistic way of looking at it.
But if it's a metropolitan organization or a local one,
doesn't matter to me as a resident.
I just want the stuff taken care of.
But I do care an awful lot about the education my kids get, and I want to have direct input into that.
And I'm saying me, but I'm also reflecting what I think
because we've talked a lot about this among the leadership of the community, I think it reflects the general populace.
There are certain things they could care less about who runs them, and there's some things they care a lot about.
So if we were to have, and what I'm saying is heresy because it's company policy to have Houston annex the Woodlands, and I think
certainly from an economic viewpoint, that is needed.
But if, what I'm saying is, if there becomes a standoff, if the suburban areas prevent that from happening, then I think that we're in compromised positions where both can benefit.
And it doesn't need to be all or nothing.
And it would perhaps behoove some people to even begin thinking about that long range.
I assume that people have done surveys, studies, what have you, to identify stuff like that.
Or are you just talking off of your own experience?
I'm talking off my own experience.
Again, this is such a sensitive issue on both sides that I'm not sure that anybody would be willing to venture to do the study because it would raise the issue.
Well, I'm not sure there's an issue.
I'm not aware of any issue.
Well, the MUDs are created initially by the developer.
Any developer can create a mud in Texas to provide water, sewage, drainage.
It's what we did here in the Woodlands with them.
And the mud has the authority to issue bonds to pay for that once you've built up enough of a population, enough of a tax base to pay the debt service on that.
So the developer front ends the financing.
takes a note back, in effect, from the developer, builds the facilities, the sewage lines, water lines, sewage treatment plants, and so forth.
And the board of the MoD agrees to pay that back according to a state-allowed formula.
And they work very well.
The next district, the Independent Taxing Institute, they would have nothing to do technically with the community association.
That's correct.
That's correct.
Those are special.
Along with the county.
That's correct.
That's correct.
The plans have to be approved by the city of Houston, because that's where we're in.
It's ETJ.
I believe they're approved by Montgomery County, but I'm not.
Certain types of districts are, and certain aren't.
I shouldn't say that.
I know certain types of districts are.
I'm not sure of all of them are.
I think all the meds have to be approved by the county and the Texas Water Commission.
But there are special purpose units of government that are allowed under state law.
And they're a convenient and effective way of getting those services into a development and used throughout suburbia.
So will the mud presently serviced in the woodlands here be extended into the new development areas or whatever?
We create muds as we go along, and I think we have eight muds today.
Oh, do you really?
Each time we go into a major new area, we create a mud.
And we also, and the muds in turn, have a contract with the San Jacinto River Authority, which is responsible for the
water plants and sewage treatment plants, and the major distribution lines.
So because of the scope, we needed an umbrella agency.
And in fact, what gave me the notion for the multiple associations with
for the community associations and the services corps.
Really, it's the way the MUDs are working.
They're doing that now, and it's working just fine.
Oh, is that right?
Sure.
That's right.
We've got eight MUDs.
We've got San Jacinto River, and they all come together in what's called the Joint Powers Agency, which is a management services corporation which manages the affairs of all the MUDs.
And we just borrowed that.
We said it would work there with the associations.
And also, I mean, I'm aware from

my work with the Community Associations Institute, that wherever you have multiple associations, there's generally some sort of common organization to help them manage their affairs, even if they're not created at the outset.
They become created because there's a manifest need to do that.
And I think we've got off to months.
pretty straightforward.
You mentioned the political issues with Houston, obviously the further community development and management.
Are there other issues that you perceive in the future that are going to
cause you more late-night meetings that you haven't mentioned?
Not that they're bad, necessarily, but I mean, you know, are there issues out there that we haven't talked about that you perceive?
I don't see any extraordinary issues coming up.
I'm sure we'll have issues from time to time, but I really don't see it.

Despite the tensions we've talked about, within the realm of my exposure, the Woodlands Corporation and the Woodlands community enjoy probably the best relationship among a developer and a community that I'm aware of.
No, that's obvious.
And my general manager of the WCA, Scott Cummings, recently attended a workshop among his counterparts
managers of community associations and large-scale developments.
And he said he wouldn't believe the horror stories that he hears.
And we're talking about mature communities, large-scale, like Irvine, California.
The developer and the communities are loggerheads all the time.
And I think
But that's because the developer doesn't respect the community, doesn't recognize that working with the community is part of the development process.
Too many developers are in the bricks and mortar business.
Even if they get themselves good planners and architects, they don't want to deal with the residents.
And if you're in a project over an extended period of time,
Brother, you better deal with it.
If for no other reason, then they can make or break a project.
On the average, over the years, 50% of the home sales in the Woodlands have come from referrals from Woodlands residents.
It tends to range from 40% to 60%, depending on...
year-to-year market conditions and whatever.
But if keeping our residents happy is good business, folks, we're going to keep them happy.
And if not entertaining them all the time, at least keeping them content.
And this is another thing I try to hit home when I'm lecturing to developers.
It's good business.
Now, some developers are in and out of a project in two or three years, and it doesn't matter.
But when you're dealing with large-scale developments that are being developed from seven to ten years or longer, you want to make sure that your residents are happy.
So you anticipate the relationship between the Woodlands Corporation and the Woodlands R.A. relationship continuing for the next, what, two decades?
Longer than that, as long as we're developing.
As long as we're in here developing, I think our residential development will probably wind down in about 25 years or so.
And then it'll be less critical.
At that point, we will have turned the other associations, at least the residential ones, over to the community.
And our commercial development will probably continue on beyond that.
We have a lot of commercial land.
But as long as we're out there developing, we're going to hopefully, you knowand I've got to say that we have enlightened management.
As the management turns, it's inevitably going to turn over two or three decades.
It's probably a good time.
Give us some sort of an overview, both from a personal and professional perspective, of how the witness is involved.
Has it met your expectations?
